WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.620
Hey there, welcome to the Posit Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:21.980
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12pm US Eastern Time. If

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:27.219
you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.219 --> 00:00:30.660
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:36.299
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.299 --> 00:00:40.340
Can't wait to see you there. Well then let's go ahead and introduce our featured leader

00:00:40.340 --> 00:00:47.820
today. I am so, so happy to be joined by Elliot Murphy. Elliot is a VP of Engineering here

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:53.060
at Posit. Elliot, it's so nice to see you today. Could you introduce yourself and tell

00:00:53.060 --> 00:01:00.060
us something that you like to do for fun as well? Yeah, so I'm Elliot. I live in Florida

00:01:00.060 --> 00:01:06.940
on a little island on the east side of Florida, which is a pretty boring little island except

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:13.139
that NASA is on the top half. And so I can actually feel the windows shake when the rockets

00:01:13.139 --> 00:01:19.540
go up every week. Blue Origin, SpaceX, Boeing, all of those rockets. And something that I

00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:25.660
like to do for fun is just be by the water. So there's dolphins in the rivers and canals

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:32.059
back here, and I just like to be outside with nature. How often does that happen? How often

00:01:32.059 --> 00:01:37.139
do rockets go off and the ground rumbles? It's easily every week. Sometimes it's every

00:01:37.139 --> 00:01:42.500
day depending on the launch schedules. That's really surprising to me. I think of launches

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:48.739
as things that happen very, very rarely. There's some big ones that get some press, right?

00:01:48.739 --> 00:01:52.699
For sending people to the space station. There's a lot of commercial activity as well,

00:01:52.699 --> 00:02:00.419
putting some more internet satellites into orbit. Wow. Okay. Well, it would be great

00:02:00.419 --> 00:02:08.059
to get some context about what you do as a VP of engineering, but also a little bit about

00:02:08.059 --> 00:02:13.179
your journey to where you are. And I'd love to talk about that because you have had a

00:02:13.179 --> 00:02:19.660
really interesting path. You did not take the traditional go get your undergrad and your

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:28.059
master's. Can you tell us a little bit about your journey? Sure. Yeah. I owe a lot to my

00:02:28.059 --> 00:02:33.580
mother and grandmother. My grandmother actually got me a computer when I was eight. So I started

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:39.339
learning the program when I was eight years old. And my mom wouldn't let us have a TV. And so that

00:02:39.339 --> 00:02:48.300
was what I did for fun. And I worked at a lot of different software jobs over the years. I tell

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:52.860
people that I'm a lifer. I'm going to keep building software for my entire life because I really,

00:02:52.860 --> 00:03:00.300
really enjoy it. But yeah, I tried and couldn't quite convince myself to finish college. I dropped

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:07.580
out several times, but have just spent a whole career building software for different people.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:14.139
And I've been at Posit now about three and a half years and really, really enjoying the people here

00:03:14.139 --> 00:03:22.539
and the mission. For a while, I worked on more general purpose systems. I worked on databases

00:03:22.539 --> 00:03:28.779
at MySQL. I worked on Linux distributions at Canonical. I worked on Ubuntu. And I loved that.

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:36.139
But then I wanted to work on tools that were a little closer to people. I've always worked on

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:42.380
tools. And so I absolutely love getting to see all the ways people use the data science tools

00:03:42.940 --> 00:03:48.139
that we produce here at Posit. I love that. I have more questions for you,

00:03:48.139 --> 00:03:53.020
but I'm getting the feedback that you sound a little bit quiet. So I was wondering if there's

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:59.020
any way we could either everybody, maybe I could turn myself down. Hold on. I'll move my mic a

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:05.339
little further away. Maybe Ellie and I can be close to the same volume. I'm not sure. Everybody

00:04:05.339 --> 00:04:13.020
let us know if Elliot sounds a little bit better now. Okay. What does a VP of engineering do?

00:04:15.179 --> 00:04:19.579
And what types of things are important to you from a philosophical standpoint

00:04:20.859 --> 00:04:28.380
for engineering and management? Yeah. So I think any engineering leader is really responsible for

00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:36.859
assembling and looking out for the team. And so at Posit about half the company is engineering

00:04:36.859 --> 00:04:42.380
roughly. We've got that half of the company divided into four groups. And I support one

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:48.299
of those groups. So all of our teams, the teams that I'm working with directly are focused on

00:04:48.299 --> 00:04:54.459
cloud and online services. So Posit Cloud and Connect Cloud and Academy, those kinds of things.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:05:03.100
And I have always tried to, I like to say that people are more important than computers.

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:08.779
The technical expertise is super important and you have to be fluent there. But every single

00:05:08.779 --> 00:05:13.660
time that you can try to create a good supportive environment for the people,

00:05:14.619 --> 00:05:20.380
the rest of it is a lot easier to deal with. A lot of the systems that we are working with,

00:05:20.619 --> 00:05:24.299
are working with, there's some pressure to keep them up, to keep them running.

00:05:25.179 --> 00:05:28.619
So it can sometimes feel like a high pressure environment. And so

00:05:31.179 --> 00:05:34.940
focusing on the people relationships, it's weird, like over the years,

00:05:37.339 --> 00:05:42.459
I feel so old saying this, but like the relationships with people tend to outlast

00:05:42.459 --> 00:05:46.779
the relationships with a given employer or a company. There's so many companies that I

00:05:46.779 --> 00:05:52.140
absolutely loved working at that no longer exist, even, but I still have relationships

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:56.859
with some of the people that I worked with there. So the human relationships are super,

00:05:56.859 --> 00:06:02.779
super important. Maybe that's part of working in technology is technology is just fast moving and

00:06:02.779 --> 00:06:07.820
fast growing and evolving. And sometimes that means that things grow and burn out over time

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:11.739
much more quickly than in other industries, right? Where insurance company is going to be around for

00:06:11.739 --> 00:06:16.619
a hundred plus years by the time you can get to it, which is my experience. I've worked for

00:06:16.619 --> 00:06:26.459
a hundred year old companies. What about your job lets you focus on the people? So I would love to

00:06:26.459 --> 00:06:32.540
talk about maintenance for a second, because you said like, okay, we have this pressure to keep

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:38.619
things running. Is there also a pressure to innovate? And is there, are those competing

00:06:38.619 --> 00:06:43.579
pressures between maintenance and innovation? There's always pressure to innovate. There's

00:06:43.579 --> 00:06:47.980
always interest in, in innovating and you want to find the new thing and you want to,

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:52.140
you want to accept that, right? Like it's important to

00:06:55.420 --> 00:07:00.299
account for and include new technologies, better ways of doing things. But it's easy to,

00:07:00.299 --> 00:07:07.179
I think it's easy to forget about the value in maintenance. When we were talking the other day,

00:07:07.179 --> 00:07:10.859
we were talking about like the road system, right? And like, you just count on the roads

00:07:10.859 --> 00:07:15.420
to be there, but so many, so many nights and weekends, there's crews that are maintaining

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:19.019
the roads and like that has to happen every season. There's so much infrastructure that we,

00:07:19.019 --> 00:07:29.980
that we count on. So I really look for ways to give ourselves credit for doing that work

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:34.700
and to kind of celebrate that maintenance work that enables everything else to run smoothly.

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:40.059
There is, there is something that is really interesting, which is like, there is so much

00:07:40.059 --> 00:07:45.579
innovation that has happened, that seems to work really well, that hasn't yet been put into

00:07:45.579 --> 00:07:50.700
practice. That's what I wanted to talk about. Yeah. Cause you, you have some stories about

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:56.220
this where you are, you're like, I have seen innovations that should be improving people's

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:02.619
lives that are a decade behind an actual application. Yeah. Yeah. I used to work and

00:08:02.619 --> 00:08:09.339
absolutely loved working there at a behavioral health and mental health startup. And the state

00:08:09.339 --> 00:08:17.019
of the art in mental health care was 12 years ahead of the common practice in clinics. And

00:08:17.019 --> 00:08:23.260
there was so much value in bringing up, you know, something from five years ago and making it

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:29.260
available to people. And so I think, I think there's just a huge amount of value in identifying

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:33.580
the good ideas from last year, the good ideas from five years ago and helping more people have

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:41.340
access to those. Yes. And this translates for me. So exactly to data science work and engineering

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:46.140
work, because I, every time I mentioned something on blue sky or LinkedIn, or here on the data

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:51.580
science hangout, that is a package I've known about and used for years, at least 10 or 15 people

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:56.219
will go, oh my gosh, I had no idea that existed. I had no idea that how long has this been out

00:08:56.219 --> 00:09:00.859
there? Right. The data pasta package is a big one. Every time I talk about data pasta, I get a

00:09:00.859 --> 00:09:06.140
wave of people that are like, wait, what? You can do that? I'm like, yeah, apparently you can do this.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:11.979
And it's existed for years. Miles's package is amazing. But there's so much like that.

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:19.179
And I feel like the, the maintenance work that happens, it has to happen. And we have it in data

00:09:19.179 --> 00:09:24.059
science as well, especially around documentation. But the push is always to move on to the next

00:09:24.059 --> 00:09:30.219
thing. How do you argue to leadership at a strategic level that that maintenance work is

00:09:30.219 --> 00:09:36.539
important to take up people's time, right? Because we, we look at this dev team and we're like, oh,

00:09:36.539 --> 00:09:42.940
they're doing too much business as usual, BAU. How do we reduce the BAU? And I know that you have

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:47.739
told me efficiencies can be found. You can sort of outsource some of that maintenance, but there's

00:09:47.739 --> 00:09:54.299
always a trade-off cost, right? There is. And I'm, I like to say I'm a fan of reality, right?

00:09:54.299 --> 00:09:59.659
So like, let's get real about what benefit we're actually getting and what, what the cost is of

00:09:59.659 --> 00:10:05.900
maintaining something. Even if I think about, you know, around the house I've got a shed or,

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:10.140
you know, something that I get some value out of, but then there's a maintenance cost also.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:14.460
And it's not always like I pay a certain fee every month. Sometimes it's a little bit lumpy,

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:20.380
like you have to do something every year and you can accumulate, especially easily in software,

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:24.780
like more systems and more things and more vendors that you're using and more software that you've

00:10:24.780 --> 00:10:30.219
built and is now kind of sitting there supposedly running quietly. But all of that represents like

00:10:30.219 --> 00:10:37.260
this growing maintenance burden. And so I really, really like thinking about it from like a budgetary

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:43.820
perspective, like we're spending this much time on, on these systems. And do we want to seek

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:47.900
efficiency on that maintenance or do we want to actually remove some of those systems completely

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:54.059
and consolidate? Or do we want, do we think it's well worth it and we should actually increase

00:10:54.059 --> 00:10:58.059
that, the maintenance, because we're getting so much value out of that when we can see how

00:10:58.059 --> 00:11:03.500
we can get value for years to come out of it. So people have been so supportive, you know,

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:08.140
in other parts of the business at every organization I've, I've been at, when you're

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:14.780
able to, to participate in the conversation, thinking about the health of the overall business

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:17.820
and accept that there's trade-offs and just involve them in the conversation. It doesn't

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:22.539
need to be like this technical debt is so important. It really should be about the health

00:11:22.539 --> 00:11:28.140
of the overall business. Well, this is a great topic to bring Javier in because Javier had a

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:33.260
question in the Slido and I would love him to ask that live so he can sort of add details around it.

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:35.260
Javier, are you available to ask that live?

00:11:37.659 --> 00:11:38.140
Thanks, Sue.

00:11:39.179 --> 00:11:41.099
There he is. Hey, yeah.

00:11:41.099 --> 00:11:43.580
My composite shirt from a few years ago, so.

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:44.080
Nice.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:49.739
Yeah, my question was basically around,

00:11:52.140 --> 00:12:01.179
I feel like there's a balance between engineers, you know, data scientists wanting to incorporate

00:12:01.179 --> 00:12:07.099
best practices in everything they do, but sometimes that is like a monumental effort

00:12:07.739 --> 00:12:13.820
that feels like a lot of innovations that come out of like very fast prototyping or tinkering,

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:19.580
or, you know, more of like a minimalist type of production style, like, or development style.

00:12:21.099 --> 00:12:24.780
I haven't, I don't have a good answer for this. Like, I haven't found what the appropriate

00:12:24.859 --> 00:12:33.020
balance is. I have seen big sort of best practice projects just go like off the rails. Like now

00:12:33.020 --> 00:12:38.460
we've created something so complex that what we thought was going to make it easier for others

00:12:39.419 --> 00:12:45.020
is maybe even more challenging now. So, you know, kind of an open-ended question for you.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:52.059
Yeah, there's, I could talk about this for, for days. I love the question.

00:12:52.619 --> 00:12:57.900
I think it's really important to, and this is not something I came up with, right? This is,

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:06.299
this is just something I've, I've seen over time, to be explicit about wanting to take on risk.

00:13:07.419 --> 00:13:12.219
It's, it's funny business, business owners and leaders understand this very well that

00:13:12.219 --> 00:13:16.780
most profit in business comes from risk. So it's, it's not that they're afraid of risk.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:22.460
They just don't want to take foolish risk. And especially in engineering or in

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:30.380
software development, it can be, or security or, or any of those things, it can be easy to think

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:35.099
about removing risk because a lot of our daily work is about removing risk and standardizing

00:13:35.099 --> 00:13:39.659
things and like making them more predictable. And it can be easy to forget the value of the risk.

00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:44.940
And so I think about this as like a dev environment versus a production environment.

00:13:45.659 --> 00:13:52.859
In even the most risk-averse organizations where lives are at stake, you have exploratory and

00:13:52.859 --> 00:14:01.179
research environments and you want to create those and, and, and, and encourage and provoke

00:14:01.739 --> 00:14:08.219
risk-taking in those environments. And then you just want to, I think a, a reasonably

00:14:08.219 --> 00:14:14.140
structured way of identifying which are the things that you want to move out of that

00:14:14.140 --> 00:14:19.179
environment into a safer, more predictable environment. And what are the, what are the

00:14:19.179 --> 00:14:22.859
additional investments that you want to make? So you don't want to make all of those.

00:14:23.659 --> 00:14:28.700
Dave Snowden likes to talk about like safe to fail experiments versus fail-safe experiments.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:34.940
So you want to do some things very, very cheaply because you want some of them to fail or you're

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:39.020
not exploring enough. And then once you've identified some things that have really good

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:43.979
potential, then you want to spend the extra time and money to sort of make them safer or more

00:14:43.979 --> 00:14:51.979
predictable and so on. So I think even the organizations that like have this identity

00:14:51.979 --> 00:14:57.820
that they carry of being extremely risk-averse spend a lot of time trying to find ways to invest

00:14:57.820 --> 00:15:02.940
in innovation in certain parts of the business. And if you can label it correctly, it can go a

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:08.940
long way towards getting permission to do those things. Yeah. I love, Elliot said to me the other

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:16.140
day, there is dignity and risk. And I feel like that belongs on a pillow somewhere, maybe a little

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:22.140
needle point. Uh, there's dignity and risk. I often think about parachutes when I think about

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:26.859
risk. I come from like a line of pilots and people who had parachutes and I grew up with parachutes

00:15:26.859 --> 00:15:34.059
all over my garage as a kid, right? And whenever I do something risky, I don't want somebody on my

00:15:34.059 --> 00:15:39.580
team who's going to take away my parachute. I want them to pack and repack my parachute

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:45.340
several times for me so that when I jump, I'm probably going to make it to the ground in one

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:50.700
piece. So the person who's just going to take away your parachute, uh, is less helpful, right? Help me

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:56.059
take this risk in a safe way. Um, Javier, that question was fantastic. Thank you for asking.

00:15:56.059 --> 00:16:03.099
And there's a poll up in Slido. If you would like to go weigh in, um, on that at the top,

00:16:03.099 --> 00:16:07.580
there is a little button where you can switch between Q and A and polls. You can go answer

00:16:07.580 --> 00:16:12.219
that question. And it's, do you have a development versus production environment at work? Do you just

00:16:12.219 --> 00:16:18.539
have production or do you have like dev test prod? Um, the majority of people are saying, yes, they

00:16:18.539 --> 00:16:23.020
do have dev test prod, but the number that is saying no, as I'm watching, it is going up the

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:28.380
percentage. I have worked at several places that have just had production, absolutely no safety or

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:32.700
guardrails at all. Um, okay. I had a question from Noor that was fantastic. Noor, would you

00:16:32.700 --> 00:16:36.780
like to hop in and ask your question live? Cause I love the philosophical take.

00:16:39.260 --> 00:16:47.580
Hello. Can you hear me? Yes. Hey, okay. This is more of a sort of broad question. Uh, but, uh,

00:16:47.580 --> 00:16:51.020
and I said, this is more of a philosophical question, but for you, what distinguishes

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:56.700
science from engineering in data and also more broadly, or do you feel it's more of an org

00:16:56.700 --> 00:17:05.180
specific, uh, specification on that level of granularity? Great question. Um, I've,

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:13.339
I've only really experienced as at like an org specific ways. Um, when I was working at the

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:19.339
healthcare startup, um, science was what they did at the university and, um, engineering was what we

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:26.219
did taking some of those papers and, and put, you know, implementing them in code. Um, but I don't,

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:31.500
I don't really have a very sophisticated take on it. It's, it's sort of an arbitrary distinction

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:37.739
in my mind. I guess, I guess maybe it's, it's, um, if you think, if you think about the,

00:17:39.579 --> 00:17:46.140
the daily experience of the person who's, who's doing a certain type of work, one is probably

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:50.380
much more exploratory and the other one is probably much more about bringing something

00:17:50.939 --> 00:17:54.939
to an audience. Um, that, that is sort of already a well-formed idea.

00:17:56.859 --> 00:18:04.219
All right. Fantastic. Thank you so much for your wonderful question is always, um, and I had a

00:18:04.219 --> 00:18:08.859
question that was from direction. And I think this is interesting. I would love to hear your take on

00:18:08.859 --> 00:18:16.619
it direction. Do you have the ability to unmute? Let's find you. Where is she?

00:18:19.099 --> 00:18:20.699
I think she's unmuting right now.

00:18:22.459 --> 00:18:31.900
Hello. Hi, I hope I'm audible. Yes. Okay. So my question was that, uh, that elitist from a

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:38.540
non-traditional background. So any resources or any books or anything that helped him bridge

00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:44.380
the gap between a non-traditional background and where currently the position he's working on,

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:49.819
right. There has to be something like any reading habit or any practices,

00:18:49.819 --> 00:18:55.660
these kinds of things apart from coding, right. There are things that soft skill that,

00:18:56.380 --> 00:19:04.380
uh, in combination with data, they like bring the best. So yes. Yeah. So I mentioned that like,

00:19:04.859 --> 00:19:08.859
I owe my career to my, my grandmother and my mother. My grandmother bought me the computer.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:14.219
My mother got me a library card and brought me to the library every single week where I would,

00:19:14.219 --> 00:19:19.180
I was homeschooled and I would bring, um, the maximum amount of books you could check out

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:24.619
from the library every single week. And, um, as I'm sitting here and it's tidy on the camera behind

00:19:24.619 --> 00:19:29.900
me, but, um, next to me, I, I literally have four foot high stacks of books because I don't have

00:19:29.900 --> 00:19:35.500
enough bookshelves in here yet. I just moved, moved houses a couple of months ago. And so, um,

00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:43.819
I have tried to fill that gap with reading, um, just compulsively is probably the right,

00:19:43.819 --> 00:19:47.739
the right word for it. Like my whole, my whole life since I was a kid, I've just read as much

00:19:47.739 --> 00:19:55.500
as I could. Some of the stuff that I have, um, enjoyed the most has been reading, reading books

00:19:55.500 --> 00:20:05.180
about, um, complexity and also a little bit of, of stuff on, um, like joint cognition. So I, I,

